data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest assertion replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.That.HasCount(users, 3);
    Assert.That.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));
    Assert.That.Contains(users, u => u.Role == "Admin");
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.That.IsNotEmpty(list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.That.HasCount(list, 3)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.All(...))` | `Assert.That.AllSatisfy(list, ...)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(item != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(item)` or `Assert.That.Contains(list, predicate)` |

These give much better failure messages — e.g., `HasCount` will report "Expected 3 but found 5" instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."

> **Note:** `Assert.That.*` APIs require **MSTest 3.8+** (the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.Assertions` package). If you're on an older version, `CollectionAssert` has basics like `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(list)`.
